<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18360509-1371">
               <interp inst="t18360509-1371" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18360509"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18360509-1371" type="date" value="18360509"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360509-1371-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1371-18360509 t18360509-1371-offence-1 t18360509-1371-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360509-1371-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1371-18360509 t18360509-1371-offence-1 t18360509-1371-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1371. <persName id="def1-1371-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1371-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1371-18360509" type="surname" value="CAULFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1371-18360509" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1371-18360509" type="occupation" value="shopman"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES CAULFIELD</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-1371-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1371-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1371-18360509" type="surname" value="ASH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1371-18360509" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE ASH</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18360509-1371-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1371-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1371-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>stealing, on the <rs id="t18360509-cd-212" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1371-offence-1 t18360509-cd-212"></join>4th of April</rs>, 2 shillings and 1 sixpence, the monies of <hi rend="smallCaps">
                        <persName id="t18360509-name-1469" type="victimName">
                           <interp inst="t18360509-name-1469" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                           <interp inst="t18360509-name-1469" type="surname" value="RUCK"></interp>
                           <interp inst="t18360509-name-1469" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                           <interp inst="t18360509-name-1469" type="occupation" value="cheesemonger"></interp>
                           <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1371-offence-1 t18360509-name-1469"></join>JOHN RUCK</persName>
                     </hi> and another, the masters of the said Charles Caulfield.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAMBERS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1470" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1470" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1470" type="surname" value="RUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1470" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RUCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in High-street, Borough, and am a cheesemonger, in partnership with my brother. About seven weeks previous to this discovery, the prisoner Caulfield came into our service as shopman—he was placed behind the retail counter for the purpose of serving—on the 4th of April, about eleven o'clock in the morning, I cleared the two tills of the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090260"></xptr>
               <p>silver in them; but previous to doing so, I prepared myself with 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. which were three half-crowns, sixteen shillings, and thirteen sixpence—I had marked them—I placed them in the tills—after that, I went to my opposite neighbours, Messrs. Barber and Jupp, the silversmith's, from whence I had a very clear view of the shop—I left the prisoner Caulfield and my son, in the shop—there were from twenty to thirty persons went in, I should suppose—I went to my shop at two o'clock, and sent Caulfield out of the way, but previous to doing that, I had prepared myself with 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. more, in marked money—I took all the silver out of the tills—there were two half-crowns marked—one half-crown, and in all, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I took that out, and put in six half-crowns, thirteen shillings, and four sixpences—they were marked with the same mark as those placed in at eleven o'clock, but it was not the same money,—I think it was not the same in again—after this I remained in the shop, and counting-house a little while, and sent my son up to dinner—I remained there till he came down, then I went up to dinner myself—I did not see Ash come to the shop—I did not know him at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the 28<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., which you took out at two o'clock, all marked? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were two half-crowns marked, a half-crown not me asked, nine shillings marked, seven shillings not marked, seven sixpence not marked, three sixpences marked.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAMBERS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did the policeman show you some marked money afterwards? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, two shillings and a sixpence—I cannot tell whether that was put in at eleven o'clock or two o'clock—there were at least, twenty or thirty customers went in between eleven o'clock and two o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1471" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1471" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1471" type="surname" value="RUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1471" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY RUCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's son. I was serving in the shop on the 4th of April, from eleven o'clock till two o'clock—I served now and then—Caulfield principally served the customers—I gave 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and one 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change, from the till—that was all I gave between eleven o'clock and ten o'clock—I do not know the parties I gave it to—I did not see Ash come in between eleven o'clock and two o'clock—I saw a man with a ship, but I do not believe it was Ash—I went up to dinner a little after two o'clock, and came down in about forty minutes—during the time I was there no one but I and the prisoner could have got to the tills.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1472" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1472" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1472" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1472" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES JAMES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable S</hi> 67.) I was watching at Messrs, Rucks on the 4th of April—I first began at a quarter before twelve o'clock, and watched till two o'clock—I saw about twenty people go in—Caulfield served them—no one went to the till but Caulfield and the last witness—I watched again after two o'clock—I had a full view of the counter in which the till was—if any one bad gone to it I must have seen them—I saw Ash go in—he went on the right hand side of the counter to look at some bacon—Caulfield came round the counter and cut three rashers of bacon which I have got—Caulfield returned behind the counter, and Ash went to the counter—I took more notice of Ash than of Caulfield—when Ash came to the counter, Caulfield was behind it, and he gave some coin to Ash, but I could not see what—he pulled out the till, and I saw some money pass—I could not see what—I did not see Ash lay down any money—I was in a position to see—he might have put a coin on the counter, but I did not see it—upon Ash going out, I followed him a little distance from the shop—I then spoke to him, and asked what he had there—he said, "Some bacon"—I asked what he gave for it—he said, "4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>."—I said, "With what coin?"—he said, "A shilling"—I said, "Are</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090261"></xptr>
               <p>you sure you gave a shilling?"—he said, "Yes"—I took him to the station, and found on him two shillings and sixpence marked money, and 7 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in copper—nothing passed as to where he got it—he said something before the inspector, which I did not hear—that was the marked money which I afterwards showed to Mr. Ruck.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1473" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1473" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1473" type="surname" value="NORTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1473" type="given" value="EDMUND"></interp>EDMUND NORTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Messrs. Barbey and Jupp. I watched Messrs. Ruck's shop on the 4th of April—I saw Ash go in there—I had a view of the counters and tills—if any persons went to the tills I could see them—I watched from half-past eleven o'clock to three or four o'clock—I saw no person go to the tills besides Caulfield and the lad—I saw Ash go into the shop—I had seen him several times before that day—he did not go into the shop till about a quarter past two o'clock—I am quite positive he is the person—he went to the right hand side of the counter to look at some bacon—Caulfield came round the counter to serve him—Caulfield then returned to the till, and appeared to me to put some money is he drew out the till—and then Ash came out of the shop—I told the constable, and he was taken—I was at the shop door when he was taken—I did not perceive Caulfield hand any thing over to Ash.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You speak of from half-past eleven o'clock? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—Ash could not have got behind the counter without my seeing him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1474" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1474" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1474" type="surname" value="RUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1474" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RUCK</persName>
                  </hi>. This two shillings and sixpence is part of my marked money—I watched the shop from eleven till two o'clock.</p>
               <p>Caulfield's Defence. Henry Ruck served Ash twice—I attended him the third time he came in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">HENRY ROCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this the sort of ship that the person brought in? (producing one.) <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe it is—I cannot say that Ash did not bring it in, but I do not believe he was the person—I my recollection points to a different person, but I will not swear he was not the me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Ash</hi>. I am the person who took the ship in—the policeman did not tel you that I said to him, that the bacon I had been to purchase, was for a riend in the Marshalsea, named Roberts.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1475" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1475" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1475" type="surname" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1475" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES JAMES</persName>
                  </hi>. He did not tell me so, but he mentioned it to the Magistrate, who sent an officer to inquire there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">HENRY RUCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you give in the course of that day two shillings and sixpence? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> All I gave was 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You saw some persons come with a ship like that into the shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he purchased some goods of me—I think a 1/4 lb. of butter, and two gga—I do not recollect what they came to—I did not give two shillings a change—only 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi> to <hi rend="smallCaps">JOHN RUCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the money counted after Ash was apprehended? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was—there was then 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in the till—it was five half-crowns marked, (one less than I put in); two not marked; mine shillings, marked; five not marked—the increase of copper was not more the 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—an hour and a half elapsed before I counted the money—I did not ount the copper.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What would be an ordinary receipt from eleven to twelve o'clock? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should think at least 40<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you stay in the counting-house when your son went up to diner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was there part of the time—I saw a man go in with a ship a little after eleven o'clock, but I should certainly say it was not the prisoner Ash—I had been watching in an opposite shop, just inside the door-way, which islevated three steps, so that we had a complete view—during the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090262"></xptr>
               <p>time that Ash came my son was at dinner, and I was there—I cannot say that I saw him come in—I do not remember seeing him come in particularly—I could see in the counting-house what passed in the shop—I did not know Ash was apprehended till the officer came and told me—I do not mean that my eye was on the shop all the time, because I know that others were watching the shop.</p>
               <p>Ash. I was examined five times—there was a person named Rickasby there each time with Mr. Ruck—he stated that he would give Mr. Ruck 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to prosecute me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1476" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1476" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1476" type="surname" value="RUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1476" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RUCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I do not know a person of that name—this is the first I have heard of it—no one had said any thing to influence me in doing this.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18360509-1371-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1371-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1371-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>
               </p>
